{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Duality"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The Lagrangian\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we have a standard optimization problem, which may not be convex.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\text{minimize}  \\; & f_0(x)      &     \\\\\n",
    "\\text{subject to}\\; & f_i(x)\\leq 0& i=1,\\ldots,m \\\\\n",
    "& h_i(x) =   0& i=1,\\ldots,p\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "Where $x\\in \\mathbf{R}^{n}$. We assume the domain $\\mathcal{D} = \\bigcap_{i=1}^m\n",
    "\\mathbf{dom} f_i \\cap \\bigcap_{i=1}^p \\mathbf{dom} h_i$ is nonempty.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The Lagrangian $L\\colon (\\mathbf{R}^{n}\\times \\mathbf{R}^{m}\\times \\mathbf{R}^{p})\\to R$\n",
    " associated with the problem as \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "L(x,\\lambda,\\nu) = \n",
    "f_0(x) \n",
    "+ \\sum_{i=1}^{m} \\lambda_i f_i(x)\n",
    "+ \\sum_{i=1}^{p}  \\nu_i h_i(x),\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "where the idea is to express the constraints by augmenting the objective function with a weighted sum of them. The vectors $\\lambda$ and $\\nu$ are called the *dual variables* or *Lagrange multiplier vectors* associated with the\n",
    "original problem."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This has an interesting interpretation. When the problem is in objective function + constraint form, we are completely agnostic to \"how well\" the constraints are satisfied, as long as the point is feasible. If there are multiple points in $X_{opt}$, they are all equally optimal.\n",
    "\n",
    "With the Lagrangian, we remove the idea of feasibility. Now, if you want to violate a constraint, you pay for it with price $\\lambda_i$ or $\\nu_i$ (Stephen Boyd calls these \"irritation functions\"). But conversely, if you come in \"under budget\" on a constraint, *you get a subsidy* $\\lambda_i$ or $\\nu_i$. In that sense, the Lagrangian cares not only about how small you can make the objective function, but how well you do on the constraints. In that case, we **do** care about how well the constraints are satisfied.\n",
    "\n",
    "If we wanted the Lagrangian formulation to reject any unfeasible points, we simply choose the $\\lambda_i$ for example to take a value of $\\infty$ outside of the feasible set to express \"infinite displeasure\" with violating the constraints.\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Lagrange dual function\n",
    "\n",
    "The Lagrange dual function as the minimum value of the Lagrangian over $x$. For\n",
    "$\\lambda\\in \\mathbf{R}^{m}$, $\\nu \\in \\mathbf{R}^{p}$,\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "g(\\lambda,\\nu) \n",
    "= \\inf_{x\\in D} L(x,\\lambda,\\nu)\n",
    "= \\inf_{x\\in D} \\left(\n",
    "f_0(x) \n",
    "+ \\sum_{i=1}^{m} \\lambda_i f_i(x)\n",
    "+ \\sum_{i=1}^{p}  \\nu_i h_i(x),\n",
    "\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "The dual function bounds the optimal value $p^*$ below **on the feasible set**. If $x$ is not feasible, then the contraints add to the Lagrangian and the value could clearly exceed $f_0(x)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "We give some 1D examples for intuition.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Single inequality constraint**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "f0 = lambda x: 2 + np.exp(-x)*np.sin(np.pi*x)\n",
    "f1 = lambda x: x**2 - 1\n",
    "L = lambda x, λ: f0(x) + λ*f1(x)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x = np.linspace(-2, 2, 200)\n",
    "\n",
    "# where the feasible set is\n",
    "where_feas = f1(x) <= 0\n",
    "where_infeas = f1(x) > 0 \n",
    "\n",
    "x_feas = x[where_feas]\n",
    "x_infeas = x[where_infeas]\n",
    "\n",
    "x_star = x_feas[np.argmin(f0(x_feas))]\n",
    "p_star = np.min(f0(x_feas))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(-0.5929648241206029, 0.2672746166210562)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_star, p_star"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 360x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(5,5))\n",
    "ax.plot(x, f0(x), label=r'$f_0(x)$')\n",
    "ax.plot(x, f1(x), label=r'$f_1(x)$')\n",
    "\n",
    "λs = np.linspace(0,1,5)\n",
    "for λ in λs:\n",
    "    ax.plot(x, L(x, λ), ':', color='gray')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.scatter(x=x_star, y=p_star, c='k', label=r'$p^*$')\n",
    "\n",
    "ymin, ymax = ax.viewLim.y0, ax.viewLim.y1\n",
    "ax.fill_between(x=[-1,1], y1=[ymin,ymin], y2=[ymax, ymax],\n",
    "                color='grey', alpha=0.1, \n",
    "                label='feasible set')\n",
    "plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.4,1))\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The dual function $g(\\lambda)$ is a function of $\\lambda > 0$ only."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# compute the dual function\n",
    "λs = np.linspace(0,1,50)\n",
    "g = np.zeros_like(λs)\n",
    "for idx, λ in enumerate(λs):\n",
    "    g[idx] = np.min(L(x, λ))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.plot(λs, g, label=r'$g(\\lambda)$')\n",
    "plt.plot(λs, np.ones_like(λs)*p_star, 'k--', label='p^*')\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r'$\\lambda$')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*Example: minimizing* $x^Tx$"
   ]
  },
